23 is the latest approved patch-set.
No files were changed between the latest approved patch-set and the submitted one.
Cool. A lot cleaner code

There are still lot of places this D-bus msg errors are not handled properly.
using this utility everywhere while calling setProperty may solve all error handling issues
```#include <string_view>```
Ack
use else if?
Why?  We have tests that explicitly check for the pattern of return then else if, and suggest what's here.
understand

can we add one common error trace which include errorName so that don't need to add a trace in each if check

BMCWEB_LOG_WARNING("DBUS error: {}", errorName);
I would prefer not, simply because BMCWEB_LOG tracks the file location and line number in the log statement.  If we combine them all, then we'd also have to explicitly log what error we saw.
ok
And we would had an if here for errorName == ...InvalidArgument ? And whatever other messages we support
can we add checks for all errors parsed in existing setProperty calls?

I'm assuming had == add in the above.

I think so?  I'm open to other options, but this seemed easy and clean.

as we roll in checks, we can add more, unless you want to consolidate a list of all?  It's non trivial to consolidate the list of every possible error, so I'd like to see at least some indication that this stuff works better before we go and do that.

This commit covers all the errors present in the things that were tested.
yeah, == is better
ok
Marking resolved.

Can this have a

BMCWEB_LOG_ERROR("D-Bus responses error: {}", ec);
ACK
Added.

I think this `res` seems not set by `setDbusProperty()`

```
asyncResp->res.jsonValue[serverType]["RemoteRoleMapping"][index]
                                      ["RemoteGroup"] = *remoteGroup;
```

Correct.

The intention of this patch is to make things correct.  Technically, this should've returned the WHOLE resource, not just the one property that got set, so it's unlikely any client could've relied on it.

I think this `res` seems not set by `setDbusProperty()`

```
asyncResp->res.jsonValue[serverType]["RemoteRoleMapping"][index]
                                      ["LocalRole"] = *localRole;
```
same answer.

Is this set by `setDbusProperty()`?
```
       asyncResp->res.jsonValue[ldapServerElementName]["ServiceAddresses"] =
            modifiedserviceAddressList;
```
Same answer as above.
Should this `serviceAddressList.front()` need to be an array, as the original code is setting as an array?

I don't understand what you're asking.

serviceAddressList is a vector.

The code that was here previously was only setting the first element of the array (see like 801 in the old code).

While I agree, this is probably not ideal, I think the new code is no less incorrect than the old code.

Agreed.  
setProperty is done correctly with the first element before and after.

(I was wondering about asyncResp->res setting with array, but it is a separate point).
I def like the direction!
sdbusplus::message::object_path(dbusObjectPath)?
Don't see this "messages::success" in the new function. Is it needed?

There's two things we could return.

200 + the representation of the object
204 no content and an empty payload

This commit opts for the second but we could certainly discuss other options (one of the things I called out in the commit message).

Hmm, yeah, 204 feels like it makes the most sense as most set property operations aren't returning anything. Another good part of this commit is we'll get a consistent response. Callers can always override if they have a special need.

`redfish::` is not needed, as this method's already in the same namespace?
Same for other files as well: systems.hpp, account_service.hpp, update_service.hpp
"objectPath" should be of type sdbusplus::message::object_path?

Object_path can be constructed from std::string, that's why this code still compiles.  Ideally, yes, every dbus path would be using type safe path objects, but the old code wasn't type safe, so this still works.  I'd like to avoid structural changes unrelated to setProperty in this patch.  It's certainly something we could clean up in another patch.
Fixed to remove redfish:: in all the files.
Noted
It should be `vectorDomainname`?
Good catch!  Fixed.
Unused. Should be deleted.
Has been removed.

Can we have the Dbus service names and interface names defined globally and use here?
Can see quite a copies in this file actually.

> Can we have the Dbus service names and interface names defined globally and use here?
> Can see quite a copies in this file actually.


Why does that matter?  Duplicate constexpr strings get deduplicated in GCC, so it doesn't effect the binary size.  I'd rather have the call site be clear when people debug, and not have to go to a central location to find all possible names.
Acknowledged

Can we add other defined common errors here?
Or, are we planning to add errors here as and when we modify each files w.r.t this change?

> Can we add other defined common errors here?
> Or, are we planning to add errors here as and when we modify each files w.r.t this change?

Could we make this more definitive before merging. i.e. "This standardizes the return code to 204 for all successful calls"
Testing? Unit tests + tested one of these?
Added testing statement to the commit message.

Hi Ed
I have tested this patch by performing few patch operations with this commit
during set property failures/errors it returns HTTP/1.1 201 Created and redfish errors are not populated
Can you put the command that you used?
curl -k -H "X-Auth-Token: $bmc_token" -D headers.txt -X PATCH -D patch.txt -d '{"HostName": "openbmc@#"}' https://${bmc}/redfish/v1/Managers/bmc/EthernetInterfaces/eth0
It looks like a HostName set error previously would only ever return 500 internal error in all cases.  What were you expecting to see, and what did you see?

I just tried:

```
curl  -k --user "root:0penBmc" -H "Content-Type: application/json" -X PATCH -d '{"HostName":"openbmc@#"}' https://192.168.7.2/redfish/v1/Managers/bmc/EthernetInterfaces/eth0
```

And the response was

```
curl  -k --user "root:0penBmc" -H "Content-Type: application/json" -X PATCH -d '{"HostName":"openbmc@#"}' https://192.168.7.2/redfish/v1/Managers/bmc/EthernetInterfaces/eth0
{
  "error": {
    "@Message.ExtendedInfo": [
      {
        "@odata.type": "#Message.v1_1_1.Message",
        "Message": "The property 'HostName' with the requested value of '\"openbmc@#\"' could not be written because the value does not meet the constraints of the implementation.",
        "MessageArgs": [
          "HostName",
          "\"openbmc@#\""
        ],
        "MessageId": "Base.1.16.0.PropertyValueIncorrect",
        "MessageSeverity": "Warning",
        "Resolution": "No resolution is required."
      }
    ],
    "code": "Base.1.16.0.PropertyValueIncorrect",
    "message": "The property 'HostName' with the requested value of '\"openbmc@#\"' could not be written because the value does not meet the constraints of the implementation."
  }
}%
```

is that different behavior than you're seeing?

Yes I have tested other patch operations, this commit works as expected.
the build I am using does not have networkd commit to return InvalidArgument error so HostName patch did not work as expected on the build.
Thank you

I think this discussion can be closed.  Patchset appears to be working as designed.

If you find anything else that doesn't work to your expectation, please feel free to let me know.
